NetworkPolicy Blocking Traffic

Your pods are running.

Services are healthy.

DNS resolution is working.

Yet applications cannot communicate with each other.

❌ Connection Timeout

❌ Service Unreachable

❌ Intermittent Connectivity Issues

One common cause is a NetworkPolicy blocking traffic.

Recently, I encountered a situation where an application pod could not connect to a backend database service even though both pods were healthy and running.

🔍 My troubleshooting approach:

✅ Verified pod and service status

✅ Reviewed NetworkPolicy configurations

✅ Checked namespace-level policies

✅ Tested connectivity using curl and nc

✅ Verified ingress and egress rules

✅ Compared pod labels with policy selectors

✅ Analyzed traffic flow between workloads

✅ Reviewed CNI plugin logs

🎯 Root Cause:

A newly created NetworkPolicy allowed only specific application pods to communicate with the database service.

The affected pod was missing the required label, causing traffic to be blocked.

After updating the pod labels and validating the policy selectors, connectivity was restored.

💡 Key Takeaway:

When troubleshooting connectivity issues in Kubernetes, don't focus only on Services and DNS.

Always verify:

• NetworkPolicies

• Pod labels

• Namespace selectors

• Ingress rules

• Egress rules

• Service connectivity

• Traffic flow paths

Useful commands:

kubectl get networkpolicy

kubectl describe networkpolicy <policy-name>

kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- curl <service>

kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- nc -zv <service> <port>

Remember:

📌 Service Exists ≠ Traffic Allowed

📌 NetworkPolicies act like firewalls for pods.

📌 A single restrictive policy can block critical application communication.

Every troubleshooting session improves our understanding of Kubernetes security and networking.
